As a battery expert I would like to point out that the support foil in nickel batteries (NiMH or NiCad) is usually pure nickel, though lower performance batteries can use nickel plated steel.

I sprinkle flux (90% borax + 5% quartz sand + 5% charcoal powder) this is necessary for forging (forge) welding. The flux is alloyed with scale - the formed substance is sufficiently fluid and is easily displaced by deformation. In addition, the flux protects against oxygen and charcoal, carburizes the surface layer of metal - which lowers the welding temperature (if in brief).

This is not Damascus.  This is pattern welded. True Damascus is crucible steel with a vanadium impurity of .05%

Trey Farrar 
This is modern damascus steel (pattern welded steel)
Real damascus steel came from a very polluted mine in india this mine was lost in time
Real damascus steel has a pattern in any state modern damascus steel only shows a pattern when acid etched
Real damscus steel was reproduced by a proffesor in 1992 but this was for scientific purposes the steel is far too expensive to make for real world use
